  "text": "The circulation strength for all cases as a function of time nondimensionalized by the total injection time, T i , is shown in Fig. 6 . The injection conditions are identified by their maximum injection velocity and total injection time. As expected, the strength of the positive and negative rotation vortices display nearly the same behavior. The plot shows the strength of the vortex pair increases linearly during injection. Immediately after the injection ends, the circulation begins to decay exponentially. This is in contrast to the circular ring vortex experiments of Gharib et al. [CITATION_1] and the simulations of Rosenfeld et al. [CITATION_2] which show the strength of a circular ring vortex in quiescent flow decays very slowly and is nearly unchanged one injection time scale past the end of injection. This difference is ascribed to the significant viscous dissipation associated with the close proximity of the counter rotating vortex pair and the viscous losses due to the presence of the wall as compared to the ring vortex formed from a circular nozzle with no nearby surface.",
